BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:govai-us-ai-policy-program-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260724T115027Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260705
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260706
SUMMARY:Deadline: GovAI U.S. AI Policy Program
DESCRIPTION:The GovAI U.S. AI Policy Program is a bipartisan\, part-time\, 
 12-week program designed to accelerate or launch careers in U.S. AI policy
 . Open to U.S. policy professionals across government and think tanks\, it
  builds a technically-informed understanding of the AI policy landscape th
 rough guided discussion sessions\, with an emphasis on general-purpose AI.
  Topics include how general-purpose AI systems are developed\; inputs to A
 I development such as energy\, chips\, and data centers\; AI's effects on 
 productivity\, scientific discovery\, and economic growth\; national secur
 ity and great power competition\; corporate self-governance\; AI regulatio
 n in other jurisdictions\; and federal and state AI regulatory proposals i
 n the U.S. Participants also have weekly opportunities to question world-l
 eading experts\; prior guest speakers have included White House OSTP staff
 ers\, former frontier-lab employees\, and people who helped draft U.S. sta
 te- and federal-level AI policy proposals. The program runs early Septembe
 r to early December 2026 (break for Thanksgiving week) with a roughly 5-ho
 ur weekly commitment: two hours of synchronous evening sessions (EST)\, he
 ld in-person at GovAI's D.C. office near DuPont Circle or remotely with ca
 meras on\, plus three hours of independent reading and podcasts from a fre
 e syllabus. To list completion on a resume\, participants must attend 9 of
  12 sessions\, write a short policy memo or op-ed\, and pass an interview-
 based exam. Eligible participants include executive and legislative branch
  staff (fellows\, interns\, detailees\, military personnel\, national labo
 ratory personnel) and think-tank policy researchers and affiliates\, acros
 s a range of seniority levels\, with preference for the D.C. metropolitan 
 area\; participants need not currently cover AI but should aspire to a car
 eer in U.S. tech or national security policy. Selection has two stages: an
  online application with six biographical questions\, a resume\, two verba
 l reasoning questions\, and an approximately 7-minute video\; followed by 
 a 30-minute interview in July\, with final decisions in early August.\n\nO
 rganisation: Centre for the Governance of AI (GovAI)\nLocation: Washington
 \, D.C.\, USA (hybrid\; remote participation available)\nAward: Free to pa
 rticipate\; in-person attendees provided dinner (value kept at or below US
 D 20 per session)\nDuration: 12-week part-time program\, early September t
 o early December 2026 (approximately 5 hours per week)\n\nMore: https://ww
 w.governance.ai/post/govai-u-s-ai-policy-program?utm_source=artificialnouv
 eaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://www.governance.ai/post/govai-u-s-ai-policy-program?utm_source=a
 rtificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Washington\, D.C.\, USA (hybrid\; remote participation available)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:ford-foundation-technology-fellow-ai-philanthropy-2026@artificialnouvea
 u.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260724T115027Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260706
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260707
SUMMARY:Deadline: Technology Fellow: AI and Philanthropy
DESCRIPTION:The Ford Foundation seeks a two-year Technology Fellow for AI a
 nd Philanthropy\, an internally-facing role focused on cross-programmatic 
 learning and advisory support. Reporting to the Director\, Technology and 
 Society\, the AI Tech Fellow will support Foundation staff in building and
  adapting internal frameworks for evaluating AI use in ways that prioritiz
 e mission and strategy and address ethical\, sociotechnical\, and operatio
 nal considerations. Responsibilities include designing and curating hands-
 on trainings\, workshops\, and learning sessions to help staff build pract
 ical familiarity with AI tools and critically assess their value and effic
 acy\; creating accessible documentation and guides on mission-aligned AI e
 xperimentation\; curating sociotechnical conversations on how philanthropy
  and the nonprofit sector are experimenting with AI in ways that respect p
 rivacy\, safety\, and equity\; monitoring emerging global AI developments 
 and providing timely briefings to program teams\; conducting landscape res
 earch on AI initiatives in the philanthropy and social justice sectors\; a
 nd building relationships with AI researchers\, practitioners\, grantees a
 nd partners working on mission-enabling AI. The Technology Fellows Program
  is administered by Ford's Technology and Society Program and is designed 
 to increase sociotechnical capacity within the Foundation. Requirements in
 clude a minimum of 7 years working within public-interest\, government\, c
 ivil society\, or commercial technology sectors\; a baccalaureate degree o
 r equivalent experience\; demonstrated sociotechnical expertise in artific
 ial intelligence and related technologies including machine learning syste
 ms and generative AI and their societal implications\; and experience desi
 gning\, implementing or supporting AI applications and tools in a complex 
 global setting. Hybrid role based in New York (three days per week in offi
 ce). Not eligible for visa sponsorship\; candidates must be authorized to 
 work in the United States. Submit both a resume and a cover letter to be c
 onsidered.\n\nOrganisation: Ford Foundation\nLocation: New York\, New York
 \, USA\nAward: USD 166\,000 to 170\,000 annual salary\, plus comprehensive
  benefits and retirement contributions of up to 13%\nDuration: Two-year te
 rm-limited contract\n\nMore: https://fordfoundation.wd1.myworkdayjobs.com/
 en-US/FordFoundationCareerPage/details/Technology-Fellow--AI-and-Philanthr
 opy_R1294?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://fordfoundation.wd1.myworkdayjobs.com/en-US/FordFoundationCareer
 Page/details/Technology-Fellow--AI-and-Philanthropy_R1294?utm_source=artif
 icialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:New York\, New York\, USA
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:genesis-mission-ai-fellowship-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260724T115027Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260731
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260801
SUMMARY:Deadline: Genesis Mission AI Fellowship 2026
DESCRIPTION:The Horizon Institute for Public Service\, Renaissance Philanth
 ropy\, SeedAI\, and Fulcrum Science are partnering to launch a fellowship 
 that embeds technical AI talent across the US Department of Energy nationa
 l labs to advance the goals of the Genesis Mission\, DOE's flagship scienc
 e and technology initiative launched in late 2025. The Genesis Mission ide
 ntifies 26 national science and technology challenges critical to US leade
 rship and envisions a national platform connecting supercomputers\, experi
 mental facilities\, AI systems\, and unique datasets\, with DOE's 17 natio
 nal labs playing a key role. Genesis Mission AI Fellows are forward deploy
 ed to DOE national labs to bring frontier AI expertise to high-priority sc
 ientific challenges. As core members of the technical staff on a Genesis M
 ission project\, fellows work alongside national lab scientists and partne
 rs and apply AI to national priorities\, from building cutting-edge models
  of plasma dynamics in pursuit of controlled fusion to advancing state-of-
 the-art models for foundational materials discovery. Initial national lab 
 partners include Idaho National Laboratory\, Brookhaven National Laborator
 y\, and the Princeton Plasma Physics Laboratory\; additional partners may 
 be announced later. COMPENSATION/DURATION: 9-12 months starting fall 2026\
 , with a prorated total annual compensation of USD 200\,000\; fellows are 
 expected to travel to their national lab site at least once a quarter but 
 may work on-site if they prefer. ELIGIBILITY: competitive applicants shoul
 d have at least 2 years of industry experience building AI models or agent
 s (those with industry experience building AI applications or data infrast
 ructure will also be considered)\; scientific domain expertise is not requ
 ired\, but any placement will involve some training and study in a specifi
 c scientific discipline or energy topic\, supported by expert colleagues a
 t the host institution. All fellows must be eligible to work in the United
  States for the duration of the placement\; US employment visas cannot be 
 sponsored\, but US permanent residents (green card holders) are eligible. 
 APPLICATION: initial form requires a CV or resume (max 2 pages) and short-
 answer questions on motivations and experiences (max 200 words)\; successf
 ul applicants complete interviews through partner organizations and nation
 al labs\, and selected fellows are matched to partner labs by scientific d
 omain and availability. The review uses evidence-based best practices incl
 uding blind grading of application materials. TIMELINE: application deadli
 ne 31 July 2026\; final fellow selection August-September 2026\; expected 
 start fall 2026.\n\nOrganisation: Horizon Institute for Public Service (wi
 th Renaissance Philanthropy\, SeedAI\, and Fulcrum Science)\nLocation: Uni
 ted States. Fellows are forward deployed to US Department of Energy nation
 al labs (initial partners: Idaho National Laboratory\, Brookhaven National
  Laboratory\, Princeton Plasma Physics Laboratory). Remote or in-person\; 
 on-site travel at least once a quarter. Must be eligible to work in the US
  (no visa sponsorship\; US green card holders eligible).\nAward: Prorated 
 total annual compensation of USD 200\,000.\nDuration: 9-12 months\, starti
 ng fall 2026.\n\nMore: https://horizonpublicservice.org/announcing-the-gen
 esis-mission-ai-fellowship/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medi
 um=referral
URL:https://horizonpublicservice.org/announcing-the-genesis-mission-ai-fell
 owship/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:United States. Fellows are forward deployed to US Department of En
 ergy national labs (initial partners: Idaho National Laboratory\, Brookhav
 en National Laboratory\, Princeton Plasma Physics Laboratory). Remote or i
 n-person\; on-site travel at least once a quarter. Must be eligible to wor
 k in the US (no visa sponsorship\; US green card holders eligible).
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:utah-oaip-ai-research-fellow-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260724T115027Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260624
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260625
SUMMARY:Deadline: AI Research Fellow / Senior AI Policy Researcher (Utah Of
 fice of AI Policy)
DESCRIPTION:The Utah Department of Commerce\, Office of Artificial Intellig
 ence Policy\, is seeking an AI Research Fellow to help drive technical\, s
 cientific\, and policy research for Utah's AI Learning Lab. This is an app
 lied research and policy-translation role whose work should directly infor
 m regulatory decisions\, legislative recommendations\, regulatory mitigati
 on agreements\, and stakeholder strategy. The role is technical and relies
  heavily on statistical\, machine learning\, computer science\, and empiri
 cal research skills\, while also requiring strong judgment\, clear writing
 \, and the ability to operate in a small multidisciplinary team alongside 
 colleagues with policy\, business\, regulatory\, and legal expertise. The 
 Office of Artificial Intelligence Policy was created in May 2024 to system
 atically develop sensible AI policy across major impact areas such as heal
 thcare\, education\, finance\, transportation\, and consumer technology. C
 entral to the Office is the AI Learning Lab\, where industry experts\, aca
 demics\, regulators\, and policymakers work toward appropriate regulatory 
 responses to emerging AI applications\; the Office also has authority to c
 reate regulatory mitigation agreements that let responsible AI businesses 
 test products in Utah under structured conditions while the state gathers 
 evidence. KEY RESPONSIBILITIES: independently scope and execute research p
 rojects on emerging AI policy questions (defining the question\, identifyi
 ng technical and empirical evidence\, interviewing experts\, evaluating tr
 adeoffs\, and producing written recommendations)\; research the technical 
 aspects\, capabilities\, limitations\, and societal impacts of AI technolo
 gies\; evaluate evidence and forecasts on the impact of human-AI interacti
 ons on health\, economic activity\, education\, consumer welfare\, and pub
 lic institutions\; draft executive policy memos\, legislative briefings\, 
 technical explainers\, risk assessments\, and regulatory mitigation analys
 es\; interface with business leaders\, technologists\, researchers\, regul
 ators\, legislators\, and lawyers\; and advise on the development of regul
 atory and legal standards. MINIMUM QUALIFICATIONS: deep technical knowledg
 e of statistical methods\, machine learning\, and AI systems\; strong abil
 ity to translate technical and empirical evidence into practical policy op
 tions for nontechnical decision-makers\; familiarity with human-subject re
 search\, qualitative and quantitative methods\, medical or health sciences
 \, social sciences\, human-computer interaction\, or related empirical fie
 lds\; excellent problem-solving\, reliability\, and independent judgment\;
  and strong technical communication across policy\, legal\, regulatory\, b
 usiness\, and technical audiences. PREFERRED: experience implementing\, ev
 aluating\, or deploying AI systems (business\, healthcare\, government\, o
 r other applied settings)\; expertise in public policy\, law\, regulatory 
 design\, or government decision-making\; ability to evaluate technical cla
 ims\, research methods\, and evidence quality\; specific healthcare experi
 ence\; and experience supporting AI deployment in regulated environments. 
 A criminal history check is required. Recruiter: Tehra Gorski\, tgorski@ut
 ah.gov\, 801-530-6030. Application deadline 24 June 2026.\n\nOrganisation:
  Utah Department of Commerce\, Office of Artificial Intelligence Policy\nL
 ocation: Salt Lake City\, Utah\, United States. Hybrid telework may be ava
 ilable but regular in-person work is required\, and in-state work rules re
 quire all work to be performed while physically within Utah. No visa spons
 orship.\nAward: Salary: USD 33.13 to 54.01 hourly wage. Full-time\, time-l
 imited position. Job classification Research Consultant III (#16048)\; may
  underfill as Research Consultant II (#16058) with a reduced salary range.
 \nDuration: Full-time\, time-limited (Schedule Code TL).\n\nMore: https://
 utdgohcm.csod.com/ux/ats/careersite/4/home/requisition/1419?c=utdgohcm&utm
 _source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://utdgohcm.csod.com/ux/ats/careersite/4/home/requisition/1419?c=u
 tdgohcm&utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Salt Lake City\, Utah\, United States. Hybrid telework may be avai
 lable but regular in-person work is required\, and in-state work rules req
 uire all work to be performed while physically within Utah. No visa sponso
 rship.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:frame-fellowship-2-ai-safety-content-creators-2026@artificialnouveau.gi
 thub.io
DTSTAMP:20260724T115027Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260710
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260711
SUMMARY:Deadline: Frame Fellowship 2.0 (Residential Accelerator for AI Safe
 ty Content Creators) 2026
DESCRIPTION:Frame Fellowship is a 10-week residential accelerator in San Fr
 ancisco for content creators educating the public on AI safety. Frame's pr
 emise is that content creators can solve a long-standing bottleneck of exp
 anding reach and trust beyond the AI safety and effective altruism (EA) bu
 bble\; creators today hack attention\, empower mass action and shape cultu
 re. Past Frame Fellows include award-winning filmmakers\, journalists from
  leading newsrooms and ex-activists who transitioned to educating\, empowe
 ring and preparing their communities for the impacts of AGI. Frame helps a
 mplify their impact to millions of people\, connects them to funding and s
 ponsorship opportunities at organizations such as FLI\, CAIS and Seismic\,
  and helps establish their path as a leading content creator. This cohort 
 runs 10 weeks with a stronger mentor and creator network\, access to produ
 ction-ready studios in San Francisco\, housing\, food and a stipend\, plus
  connections to funding and partnership opportunities after the program. T
 WO TRACKS: (1) Independent Track\, build your own channel and become a def
 ining voice on a topic\; (2) Amplifier Track\, embed with an AI org/compan
 y and grow their reach. SUPPORT: Frame covers accommodation\, meals\, flig
 hts and a USD 10\,000 stipend for the 10 weeks so fellows can go all in\; 
 top performers may be eligible for additional grant opportunities beyond t
 he program. Early deadline: 10 July 2026. Apply at https://framefellowship
 .com/.\n\nOrganisation: Frame Fellowship\nLocation: San Francisco\, USA\; 
 residential (in person).\nAward: USD 10\,000 stipend for the 10 weeks\, pl
 us accommodation\, meals and flights covered. Access to production-ready s
 tudios in San Francisco\, a mentor and creator network\, and connections t
 o funding\, sponsorship and partnership opportunities at organizations suc
 h as FLI\, CAIS and Seismic. Top performers may be eligible for additional
  grant opportunities beyond the program. No application fee.\nDuration: 10
 -week residential program\n\nMore: https://framefellowship.com/?utm_source
 =artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://framefellowship.com/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_
 medium=referral
LOCATION:San Francisco\, USA\; residential (in person).
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:bolder-futures-fellowship-ai-for-social-good-2026@artificialnouveau.git
 hub.io
DTSTAMP:20260724T115027Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260630
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260701
SUMMARY:Deadline: Bolder Futures Fellowship 2026: AI for Social Good (spons
 ored by Micron)
DESCRIPTION:A 12-week fall fellowship that bridges emerging AI technology a
 nd the social sector: fellows gain practical\, workplace-ready AI skills t
 hrough hands-on\, interactive training while applying them to increase the
  operational capacity of a partner nonprofit. The program emphasises movin
 g past theoretical AI concepts into immediate\, real-world applications\, 
 and provides equitable access to AI training for individuals and organizat
 ions driving positive social change. WHO SHOULD APPLY: professionals and e
 merging leaders seeking practical AI skills\; prior AI experience is not r
 equired. ELIGIBILITY: applicants must be at least 18\, secure a commitment
  from a 501(c)(3) nonprofit partner\, and commit roughly 8-10 hours per we
 ek. Fully remote (sessions during 9am-5pm PT)\; stipends can only be issue
 d to individuals with US-based tax status (SSN or ITIN)\, though US-based 
 nonprofits with employees elsewhere may be considered. COMPENSATION: USD 2
 \,000 stipend upon successful completion. The program runs September to De
 cember 2026. DEADLINE: 30 June 2026\, 11:59pm PT.\n\nOrganisation: Bolder 
 Futures (sponsored by Micron)\nLocation: United States\; fully remote. Sti
 pends can only be issued to individuals with US-based tax status (SSN or I
 TIN)\; US-based nonprofits with employees elsewhere may be considered. Ses
 sions run during 9am-5pm PT.\nAward: USD 2\,000 stipend on successful comp
 letion (the program notes a comparable paid upskilling program is valued a
 t USD 7\,000 or more). No application fee.\nDuration: 12-week program\, Se
 ptember to December 2026\; roughly 8-10 hours per week\n\nMore: https://bo
 lderfutures.org/fellowships/ai-for-social-good/?utm_source=artificialnouve
 augrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://bolderfutures.org/fellowships/ai-for-social-good/?utm_source=ar
 tificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:United States\; fully remote. Stipends can only be issued to indiv
 iduals with US-based tax status (SSN or ITIN)\; US-based nonprofits with e
 mployees elsewhere may be considered. Sessions run during 9am-5pm PT.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:zwillgen-fellowship-2027-2028@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260724T115027Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260831
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260901
SUMMARY:Deadline: ZwillGen Fellowship Program 2027-2028 (Technology Law)
DESCRIPTION:The ZwillGen Fellowship is a 12-month position for recent law-s
 chool graduates and early-career attorneys interested in working at the in
 tersection of law\, technology\, and public policy. Fellows work alongside
  attorneys on matters involving privacy\, cybersecurity\, artificial intel
 ligence\, online platforms\, surveillance\, digital advertising\, fintech\
 , online safety\, and technology regulation\, contributing to client couns
 eling\, investigations\, litigation\, and emerging regulatory matters\, as
  well as research\, writing\, and speaking. The program includes a reduced
  billable target (1\,250 hours) to make room for thought leadership and en
 gagement with the technology policy\, privacy\, and civil liberties commun
 ity. ELIGIBILITY: must have graduated from law school before the program s
 tarts\; must have taken or plan to take a bar exam near the start of the F
 ellowship\; must be able to work out of the DC office and be eligible to a
 pply for admission to the DC Bar. Candidates primarily interested in tradi
 tional IP practice may find it less aligned. A small number of applicants 
 may also be considered for the Hannah Schaller Memorial Skylark Fellowship
  (privacy-law focus\, with a reduced 1\,100-hour billable target for addit
 ional community engagement). Following the Fellowship\, fellows may be inv
 ited into a full-time attorney role or supported in pursuing other technol
 ogy law and policy opportunities. APPLY with a resume\, law-school transcr
 ipt\, writing sample\, and cover letter by 31 August 2026.\n\nOrganisation
 : ZwillGen\nLocation: Washington\, D.C.\, USA (must work out of the DC off
 ice)\nAward: Salary USD 115\,000 to USD 125\,000\, with a reduced annual b
 illable target (1\,250 hours) to create space for writing\, professional d
 evelopment\, and policy engagement. No application fee.\nDuration: 12-mont
 h position beginning Fall 2027\n\nMore: https://www.zwillgen.com/careers/f
 ellowship-program/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referr
 al
URL:https://www.zwillgen.com/careers/fellowship-program/?utm_source=artific
 ialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Washington\, D.C.\, USA (must work out of the DC office)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:cisac-ai-fellowships-2026-27@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260724T115027Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260608
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260609
SUMMARY:Deadline: CISAC (Stanford): AI Fellowships 2026-2027 (Strategic Sta
 bility & Geopolitics of AI)
DESCRIPTION:For the 2026-2027 academic year\, CISAC's fellowship applicatio
 n is open for ONLY two tracks: the Artificial Intelligence in Strategic St
 ability and Military Competition Fellowship\, and the Geopolitics of Artif
 icial Intelligence Fellowship. Fellows spend the academic year in residenc
 e at Stanford engaged in research and writing\, participating in seminars 
 and collaborating with CISAC faculty and the wider community. CAREER STAGE
 S: predoctoral (currently enrolled PhD students)\, postdoctoral (completed
  PhD or DPhil)\, and junior faculty or mid-to-late-career professionals (c
 onsidered case-by-case). FUNDING: stipends are provided (predoctoral compa
 rable to Stanford Graduate Fellowships plus tuition\; postdoctoral and pro
 fessional stipends commensurate with experience)\, though exact amounts ar
 e not published. ELIGIBILITY: non-US citizens may apply and visas are avai
 lable through the fellowship. Fellowships range from nine to eleven months
  and require residence at Stanford. The deadline to apply is 8 June 2026. 
 Questions: cisacfellowship@stanford.edu.\n\nOrganisation: Center for Inter
 national Security and Cooperation (CISAC)\, Stanford FSI\nLocation: Stanfo
 rd\, California\, USA (in-residence)\nAward: Funded in-residence fellowshi
 p. Predoctoral fellows receive stipends comparable to the Stanford Graduat
 e Fellowships program\, plus CISAC pays non-matriculated student tuition\;
  postdoctoral and junior-faculty/professional fellows receive stipends com
 mensurate with experience and Stanford's established minimums. Specific do
 llar figures are not published. No application fee.\nDuration: 9 to 11 mon
 ths (2026-2027 academic year)\; in certain circumstances renewable\n\nMore
 : https://cisac.fsi.stanford.edu/cisac-fellowships?utm_source=artificialno
 uveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral#tab-116493
URL:https://cisac.fsi.stanford.edu/cisac-fellowships?utm_source=artificialn
 ouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral#tab-116493
LOCATION:Stanford\, California\, USA (in-residence)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
