BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:data-society-senior-researcher-ai-civics-2026@artificialnouveau.github.
 io
DTSTAMP:20260724T115027Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260730
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260731
SUMMARY:Deadline: Senior Researcher\, AI Civics
DESCRIPTION:Data & Society\, the independent nonprofit studying the social 
 implications of data-centric technologies and automation\, is hiring a Sen
 ior Researcher for AI Civics\, a newly launched two-year programme on civi
 c action and community control over AI. The programme aims to amplify the 
 tools of civic participation so the public can directly shape the role AI 
 plays in society\, surfacing civic tools people can use to exert political
  power over AI systems and tech platforms at community level. It co-create
 s toolkits and training resources with anchor partner organisations\, diff
 uses them through a train-the-trainer model\, and builds toward a national
  civic coalition demanding democratic accountability over AI. The Senior R
 esearcher is a subject-matter expert and lead contributor\, drawing primar
 ily on participatory methods and especially participatory action research\
 , and is responsible for one or more inter-organisational partnerships wit
 h national partner organisations working in K-12 education\, labour\, fait
 h or advocacy. Responsibilities span cultivating and stewarding relationsh
 ips with partner staff\, community members and leaders and public sector w
 orkers\; leading collaborative relationships with an anchor partner and it
 s local members for the co-creation and diffusion of AI Civics resources\;
  co-developing and iterating toolkits\, facilitation guides and training c
 urricula and running piloting\, feedback and revision cycles\; producing c
 ase studies\, educational materials\, templates\, reports\, academic publi
 cations\, lectures and public writing\; supporting facilitation preparatio
 n for co-design workshops\, train-the-trainer sessions and participatory r
 esearch activities\; developing research questions\, strategies and new ex
 ternal partnerships with the Program Director\; network communications\; p
 articipating in fundraising\, including grant applications and materials f
 or the Development Team\; and contributing to the intellectual life of the
  organisation. REQUIRED: graduate degree or equivalent\; expertise in one 
 or more sectors of interest to the programme (K-12 education\, labour\, fa
 ith groups\, or another institutional pillar of civic life as it relates t
 o data-centric technologies and AI)\; 7 to 10 years minimum experience in 
 research organisations or research environments (university\, public polic
 y\, advocacy\, government)\, inclusive of graduate work\; expertise in par
 ticipatory research methods\; a strong track record of seeing research thr
 ough to publication\; a public profile and ability to reach non-academic a
 udiences through writing and speaking\; and the ability to coordinate and 
 conduct in-depth qualitative research. PREFERRED: doctoral degree in infor
 mation science\, education\, social sciences or similar\; established rela
 tionships with relevant organisations in the programme themes\; experience
  with civic engagement or organising in nonprofit\, labour\, advocacy\, re
 search or public interest technology contexts. Reports to the Program Dire
 ctor. Data & Society requires prospective employees to be fully vaccinated
  against COVID-19. TO APPLY: submit a cover letter\, an academic CV\, and 
 the names\, affiliations\, titles\, email addresses and phone numbers for 
 three references by 30 July 2026. Applications are reviewed from 31 July 2
 026. Questions: jobs@datasociety.net. NOTE: this is a salaried job\, not a
  grant or fellowship.\n\nOrganisation: Data & Society Research Institute\n
 Location: Fully remote within the United States. Data & Society is based i
 n New York City and operates as a remote-first organisation\; occasional o
 nsite meetings possible. You must be living and authorised to work in the 
 US\; no visa sponsorship.\nAward: USD 78\,000 to 97\,000 annual salary\, c
 ommensurate with experience\, plus medical\, dental and vision insurance\,
  opt-in insurance and 401k products\, paid time off and paid federal holid
 ays. No application fee.\nDuration: Two-year full-time position\, Septembe
 r 2026 to 31 May 2028\, with no expectation of extension\n\nMore: https://
 job-boards.greenhouse.io/datasocietyresearchinstitute/jobs/8635382002?utm_
 source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://job-boards.greenhouse.io/datasocietyresearchinstitute/jobs/8635
 382002?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Fully remote within the United States. Data & Society is based in 
 New York City and operates as a remote-first organisation\; occasional ons
 ite meetings possible. You must be living and authorised to work in the US
 \; no visa sponsorship.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:lawai-academic-fellowship-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260724T115027Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260731
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260801
SUMMARY:Deadline: Law & AI Academic Fellowship
DESCRIPTION:The Institute for Law & AI (LawAI)\, an independent think tank 
 researching and advising on the legal challenges posed by artificial intel
 ligence\, is running its inaugural Law & AI Academic Fellowship for aspiri
 ng legal scholars who intend to go on the US legal academic job market. Th
 e fellowship is designed as an alternative to university-sponsored Visitin
 g Assistant Professor or law fellow positions: fellows spend the majority 
 of their time researching and writing articles for publication in law jour
 nals on the law of transformative AI\, and are prepared for the academic j
 ob market as part of a larger application package. Teaching is not require
 d\, which LawAI frames as a benefit over most university-affiliated positi
 ons\, though fellows who want teaching experience are encouraged to seek i
 t and LawAI and its affiliates may be able to help secure positions. Each 
 fellow is paired with an academic mentor from LawAI's network of affiliate
 d academics for ongoing support\, with more intensive help in the final st
 ages of the job application process including moot interviews and detailed
  feedback. Fellows may also inquire about spending time in residence at ac
 ademic institutions of interest. Candidates are selected in part on how we
 ll their research interests align with LawAI's: the institute expects AI t
 o reshape culture\, the economy\, public policy\, public administration\, 
 politics\, military affairs and geostrategy at least as profoundly as the 
 Industrial Revolution\, and asks whether a candidate's research is well-sc
 oped to changes of that magnitude. Areas of particular interest include ri
 sk regulation of transformative AI\, liability for AI harms\, AI and biose
 curity\, AI and cybersecurity\, executive branch use of transformative AI\
 , national security law\, law and AI infrastructure\, administrative law\,
  constitutional law\, international regulation\, AI in the judiciary\, and
  industrial policy. Full-time two-year role at USD 130\,000 per year\, bas
 ed in Washington DC\, Cambridge UK\, or remote. Applications close 31 July
  2026.\n\nOrganisation: Institute for Law & AI (LawAI)\nLocation: Washingt
 on DC\, USA\; Cambridge\, UK\; or remote\nAward: USD 130\,000 annual salar
 y. No application fee.\nDuration: Two years\, full-time\n\nMore: https://l
 aw-ai.org/career/academic-fellowship/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdes
 k&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://law-ai.org/career/academic-fellowship/?utm_source=artificialnou
 veaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Washington DC\, USA\; Cambridge\, UK\; or remote
END:VEVENT
